{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0f88773a-136b-4371-ba90-5096616cf660","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Recursive wildcard glob** (line 9 of `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree during evaluation. This is the single most common cause of slow evaluation, especially as the repo grows. Use a narrower glob (e.g., specific extensions or a subdirectory) or move to an itemgroup inside a target so it runs at build-time, not evaluation-time.\n\n### 2. **File I/O via property function** (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `File.ReadAllText` during evaluation blocks the evaluator on disk I/O. Property functions run synchronously and are re-evaluated on every design-time build (IDE reload, etc.). Move this to a target that reads the file only when actually needed.\n\n### 3. **Three-level import chain** (`level1 → level2 → level3`)\nEach `<Import>` adds an XML parse + evaluate pass. Three levels is modest, but the chain is entirely linear—each file does nothing but import the next and set one property. Flattening these into a single `.props` file (or at least reducing depth) would cut evaluation overhead.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order:** #1 (wildcard glob) > #2 (property function I/O) > #3 (import depth). The wildcard glob dominates in any non-trivial directory tree; the property function becomes painful under frequent IDE re-evaluation.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5ab9b6b5-a843-4da7-af3a-06fafc22758d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a clear picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.","outputTokens":449,"requestId":"781B:339A0E:1E1098F:227F7EC:69F551C1"},"id":"13fef417-e74a-4ee6-989d-cc60706d3598","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:22:25.149Z","parentId":"d92ac196-3bcc-45fd-967d-15d591727b22"}
